On Apps Script you can set up an [`onEdit`][1] trigger that retrieves the username of the editor and cell where the change was made; but you will have to keep in mind that there may be cases where the username is not retrievable (mainly if the user haven&#39;t accepted the script scopes), you can read more about those situations on [`getActiveUser`][2] docs.

You can achieve what you are requesting with the following function. It will use the [event object][3] to check if the change was made on the G column, and if it was, the email of the user (or `Unknown` if the scopes weren&#39;t accepted) will be written on the B column of the same row.

    function onEdit(e) {
      var range = e.range;
      var editor = e.user.getEmail();
      if (editor == &#39;&#39; || editor == null) {
        editor = &#39;Unknown&#39;;
      }
      if (range.getA1Notation().search(&#39;G&#39;) != -1) {
        range.offset(0, -5).setValue(editor);
      };
    }

After saving this function you will have to create a [installable trigger][4]. To do so, go to `Edit &#129094; Current project&#39;s triggers`. After that, click on `+ Add Trigger` and fill this settings:

 - Choose which function to run: onEdit
 - Choose which deployment should run: Head
 - Select event source: From spreadsheet
 - Select event type: On edit
 - Failure notification settings: as you wish

After saving the trigger you could test the function by yourself modifying a cell in the G column. Please, do not hesitate to ask for any clarification about my answer or the code itself.


